58":"1473–1558","1476–1502":"1476–1502","1480–1526":"1480–1526","1483–1517":"1483–1517","1488–1525":"1488–1525","–1558":"–1558","1470–1517":"1470–1517","1442–1509":"1442–1509","1447–1517":"1447–1517","1462":"1462","1473":"1473","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","March 1509":"maart 1509","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1502":"1502","1469":"1469","1488":"1488","1487":"1487","1476":"1476","1442":"1442","3 March 1509":"3 maart 1509","1509":"1509","1517":"1517","1549":"1549","1526":"1526","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wye, Kent, England":"Wye, Kent, England"},"en":{"1462–3 March 1509":"1462–3 March 1509","1462–1509":"1462–1509","1469–Male":"1469–Deceased","1470–1549":"1470–1549","1473–1558":"1473–1558","1476–1502":"1476–1502","1480–1526":"1480–1526","1483–1517":"1483–1517","1488–1525":"1488–1525","–1558":"–1558","1470–1517":"1470–1517","1442–1509":"1442–1509","1447–1517":"1447–1517","1462":"1462","1473":"1473","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","March 1509":"March 1509","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1502":"1502","1469":"1469","1488":"1488","1487":"1487","1476":"1476","1442":"1442","3 March 1509":"3 March 1509","1509":"1509","1517":"1517","1549":"1549","1526":"1526","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Wye, Kent, England":"Wye, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Masters","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational and occupational name from Middle English <i>(atte) maisteres</i> ‘(at the) master's (house)’, a name for someone who lived or worked there, normally a servant. Compare   Master   and   Masterman  , and for the type compare   Maidens  ,   Monks  ,   Parsons  .","variant of   Master  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Master","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Amar, Dhimant, Pravin, Amit, Aruna, Bhanu, Gaurang, Gopal, Haren, Jagu, Jayesh, Kalpesh.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>maister</i> ‘master’ (Old French <i>maistre</i>). The word had a wide range of applications, and the reference in surnames may be to a schoolmaster, to the master of a farm or house, to the master of an apprentice, or to a ship's captain. In Scotland the eldest sons of barons and the uncles of lords were called <i>Masters</i>, but this is not primarily a Scottish surname.","German: dialect form of   Meister   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Maidens","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire):","occupational or habitational name from Middle English <i>(atte) maydenes</i> ‘(at the) maiden's or maidens' (house)’, a name for someone who lived or worked at such a house. Compare   Masters   and   Parsons  .","post-medieval variant of   Maiden  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Marsters","meanings":["English: variant of   Masters  . <i>Marsters</i> is the predominant surname on Palmerston Island, Cook Islands, South Pacific, deriving from a settler and owner reputedly born in Leicestershire."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Masters was born in 1462, in Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Masters III, was 20 and his mother, Agnes Webbe, was 15. He married Agnes Denyse in 1487. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 3 March 1509, in his hometown, at the age of 47, and was buried in Kent, England, United Kingdom.